But the left might also do well to consider another idea that has fallen into obscurity: converting the military-industrial complex to peacetime work.
The military-industrial complex, he argued, had robbed Americans of a manufacturing-based economy, with stable wages for the working class.
The solution was left to Harvard’s John Kenneth Galbraith, who had a grander vision for defense conversion: nationalizing the military-industrial complex.
Herein lies an opportunity for proponents of the Green New Deal to regulate military contractors and finance job growth by converting the military-industrial complex to peaceful ends.
The military-industrial complex is not just a product of the “foreign-policy establishment.” It protects and strengthens that establishment.